        <!-- H2 #3 -->
        <h2>Key Rules of the Calculation</h2>
        <p>To use a commuter allowance tool correctly, you must keep three fundamental rules in mind:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>One-Way Distance Only:</strong> You can only claim the distance for a one-way trip, not the round trip.</li>
            <li><strong>Actual Working Days:</strong> You can only claim the allowance for days you physically traveled to your workplace.</li>
            <li><strong>The Shortest Route:</strong> The tax office (Finanzamt) generally expects you to calculate using the shortest regular road connection.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- H2 #4 -->
        <h2>The Annual Maximum Limit and the Car Exception</h2>
        <p>The German tax office sets a maximum annual limit of €4,500 for the commuter allowance. However, there is a major exception to this rule based on your mode of transport.</p>
        <p>If you commute using public transport, a bicycle, or as a passenger in a carpool, your annual deduction cannot exceed €4,500. If you use your own personal car or a company car, this €4,500 cap does not apply. Car drivers can claim the full calculated amount.</p>

