        <h2>How to Calculate Your Total Deduction</h2>
        <p>The mathematical formula for the 2026 tax year is very straightforward:</p>
        <p><em>One-Way Distance (km) × €0.38 × Number of Working Days = Total Tax Deduction</em></p>
        <p>For example, if you commute 25 km to your office for 220 days, your calculation is: 25 × €0.38 × 220 = €2,090. Since this is below the €4,500 cap, you can deduct the full amount.</p>

        <!-- H2 #7 -->
        <h2>What About Working from Home (Home Office)?</h2>
        <p>If you work from home, you cannot claim the commuter allowance for those specific days because you did not travel. Instead, you can claim the Home Office Allowance (Homeoffice-Pauschale).</p>
        <p>For every day you work entirely from home, you can claim a flat rate of €6.00, up to a maximum limit of €1,260 per year (which equals 210 working days).</p>
        <p><em>Need to calculate your home office days? Try our dedicated <a href="https://pendlerpauschalerechner.de/homeoffice-allowance-calculator/">Homeoffice Allowance Calculator</a>.</em></p>

        <!-- H2 #8 -->
        <h2>How to Claim the Allowance on Your Tax Return</h2>
        <p>To get your money back, you must submit an annual German tax declaration (Steuererklärung). You can do this securely online using the official German government tax portal known as <a href="https://www.elster.de/eportal/start" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ELSTER</a>, or through popular English tax software apps.</p>
        <p>You will need to fill out Anlage N (the form for income from employment). You do not need to attach train tickets or gas receipts to your tax return initially, but you should keep them safe just in case the tax office asks for proof.</p>

